    "Let me analyze this reaction to identify the roles of reagents, solvent, and catalyst.\n\nThe reaction SMILES: C[C@H](N)c1ccccc1.O=C(Cl)C(=O)c1ccccc1.c1ccccc1 >> C[C@H](NC(=O)C(=O)c1ccccc1)c1ccccc1\n\nReactants:\n1. C[C@H](N)c1ccccc1 - (R)-α-methylbenzylamine (amine nucleophile)\n2. O=C(Cl)C(=O)c1ccccc1 - phenyloxalyl chloride (acyl chloride)\n3. c1ccccc1 - benzene\n\nProduct: C[C@H](NC(=O)C(=O)c1ccccc1)c1ccccc1 - N-acylated amine\n\nThe reaction is an acylation: the amine reacts with the acyl chloride to form an amide. The Cl is displaced and the NH2 becomes NHC(=O).\n\nNow, what role does benzene (c1ccccc1) play? Benzene is listed as a reactant but doesn't appear in the product. In this reaction, benzene serves as the solvent. It's a common solvent for Schotten-Baumann type acylation reactions or similar acyl chloride-amine reactions.\n\nSo the roles are:\n- C[C@H](N)c1ccccc1 (amine): reagent (nucleophile/substrate)\n- O=C(Cl)C(=O)c1ccccc1 (phenyloxalyl chloride): reagent (acylating agent)\n- c1ccccc1 (benzene): solvent\n\nThere's no catalyst in this reaction.\n\nLet me format this as a condition_role_mapping:\n\nReagents: C[C@H](N)c1ccccc1 (amine substrate), O=C(Cl)C(=O)c1ccccc1 (acylating agent)\nSolvent: c1ccccc1 (benzene)\nCatalyst: none"
